  "category_subtitle": "Learn how to count building floors in Japanese using 階",
  "category_detail": "<b>Counting Floors in Japanese</b><br><br>In Japanese, floors of a building are counted using the counter <b>「階」(かい / kai)</b>.<br><br>This counter is used when referring to floors in buildings such as apartments, offices, shopping malls, and hotels.<br><br><b>Important Sound Changes</b><br>Some numbers change pronunciation when combined with 階.<br><br><span class=\"example\">1階</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(いっかい / ikkai)</span><br><span class=\"example\">3階</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(さんがい / sangai)</span><br><span class=\"example\">6階</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(ろっかい / rokkai)</span><br><span class=\"example\">8階</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(はっかい / hakkai)</span><br><span class=\"example\">10階</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(じゅっかい / jukkai)</span><br><br><b>Common Usage</b><br><span class=\"example\">レストランは三階にあります。</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(resutoran wa sangai ni arimasu)</span><br>Meaning: The restaurant is on the third floor.<br><br>This counter is very common when giving directions inside buildings.",
